National Police Commissioner, Khehla Sitole commits to acting on corruption within 14 days. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - National Police Commissioner, Khehla Sitole has confirmed that the Hawks are probing alleged Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) tender fraud in the police service. A Sunday Times report revealed four contracts worth R540-million are under investigation. READ: Police commissioner reshuffles top management Sitole says if the implicated officials are found guilty of corruption, they will be brought to book.  National Police Commissioner, Khehla Sitole commits to acting on corruption within 14 days. Courtesy #DStv403 Sitole says, when he took office, he ordered a review of procurement processes. "The reason why the Hawks are investigation is part of the overhaul of the procurement investigation. I have also put in oversights around the procurements. If there is any suspicion, the matters must be investigated immediately. Investigations, both internal and criminal, is because of our zero-tolerance approach to corruption as well as the procurement maladministration." READ: 12 SAPS officers arrested for corruption Sitole has confirmed that companies investigated for PPE corruption have done business with the police.